#synthesis(title: [Food Insecurity: A New Axis of ME/CFS Disease Burden and Clinical Exposure])[
The convergence of cross-national evidence establishes food insecurity as a measurable consequence of ME/CFS and Long COVID — one that is both a downstream product of disease-driven employment loss and a potential upstream modifier of disease trajectory. Four convergent themes structure this evidence:

*Theme 1: Disease drives deprivation.* Employment loss (Bowden 2026: 18.3% ME/CFS employment vs. 83.8% general population @bowden2026mecfslabourmarket) produces income reduction → food insecurity. This chain is independently replicated in Long COVID (Datta 2025: 1–11 percentage-point FI increase across income strata @datta2025longcovidfinancial), with employment loss mediating 6–20% of the effect.

*Theme 2: Deprivation may reciprocally worsen disease.* The strongest evidence is from Long COVID (Lin 2025: aOR 1.73 for FI→LC; aOR 0.70 for recovery among food-insecure @lin2025longcovidfoodinsecurity), but the implication for ME/CFS is direct: if nutritional deficiency impairs mitochondrial function, immune surveillance, and post-exertional recovery, the same bidirectional loop likely operates. The severity spiral hypothesis (@spec:fi-severity-spiral, cert 0.40) assembles this logic from established unidirectional links — it has not been directly observed.

*Theme 3: The null hypothesis remains unfalsified.* Jones 2017 found limited evidence for dietary modification in CFS @jones2017dietarycfs; some patients report no dietary benefit. Until a well-powered RCT of food assistance vs. usual care demonstrates functional improvement, food programs should be justified on quality-of-life and financial grounds, not disease-modification grounds (@spec:fi-null-hypothesis, cert 0.25).

*Theme 4: Immediately actionable structural interventions exist.* The HIV food assistance template (@spec:hiv-food-assistance-template) provides a 15-year clinical precedent. Routine FI screening with the validated Hunger Vital Sign (@oq:fi-screening-protocol) would identify the estimated 25–35% of ME/CFS clinic patients who are food-insecure with current clinician-recognition rates below 5%.

The central open question is not *whether* food insecurity exists in ME/CFS — the evidence is clear that it does — but whether resolving it alters disease outcomes. A prospective study tracing FI onset to subsequent functional decline, or a pilot trial of medically tailored meals for severe ME/CFS, would transform this from a documented inequality into a tractable intervention target.

*Consequence:* Food insecurity gives the ME/CFS community an evidence-based socioeconomic metric that is independent of contested pathophysiology — objective, measurable, and actionable through existing policy levers (disability benefit adequacy, SNAP enrollment, clinical screening). For patients, this adds a dimension of disease burden that clinicians and policymakers can respond to without needing to resolve the underlying disease mechanism.
] <syn:food-insecurity-model>

